root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>14993</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Lemma</fr:taxon><fr:addr>jms-004Z</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-004Z.xml</fr:route><fr:title>Uniqueness of downshifts</fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2023</fr:year><fr:month>4</fr:month><fr:day>15</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
href="jonmsterling.xml"
type="local"
addr="jonmsterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex>N \in \mathcal {D}</fr:tex> be a <fr:link
href="jms-004B.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-004B">negative</fr:link> object in a <fr:link
href="jms-004Q.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-004Q">positively univalent deductive system</fr:link>; then the type of <fr:link
href="jms-004P.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-004P">downshift structures</fr:link> on <fr:tex>N</fr:tex> is a proposition. In this case, we may refer to the property of <fr:tex>N</fr:tex> <fr:em>having a downshift</fr:em>.</fr:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="false"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>14101</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:addr>#496</fr:addr><fr:route>unstable-496.xml</fr:route><fr:date><fr:year>2023</fr:year><fr:month>4</fr:month><fr:day>15</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
href="jonmsterling.xml"
type="local"
addr="jonmsterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:parent>jms-004Z</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
  <fr:p>Let <fr:tex>w_0:N \vdash  P_0</fr:tex> and <fr:tex>w_1:N \vdash  P_1</fr:tex> be two <fr:link
href="jms-004P.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-004P">downshift structures</fr:link> on <fr:tex>N</fr:tex>, whose inverse unwrapping maps are written <fr:tex>u_0,u_1</fr:tex> respectively. We wish to identity <fr:tex>{ \mathopen {} \left ( P_0,w_0 \right ) \mathclose {}}</fr:tex> with <fr:tex>{ \mathopen {} \left ( P_1,w_1 \right ) \mathclose {}}</fr:tex>.</fr:p>

  <fr:p>All four maps <fr:tex>w_0,w_1,u_0,u_1</fr:tex> are thunkable: the wrapping maps are thunkable by definition, and the unwrapping maps are thunkable because they are valued in a negative object. Thus we have a thunkably invertible thunkable map <fr:tex>u_1;w_0 : P_1 \vdash  P_0</fr:tex>; because <fr:tex>\mathcal {D}</fr:tex> is assumed <fr:link
href="jms-004Q.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-004Q">positively univalent</fr:link>, we may identify the pairs <fr:tex>{ \mathopen {} \left ( P_0, 1 _{ P_0 } :P_0 \vdash  P_0 \right ) \mathclose {}}</fr:tex> and <fr:tex>{ \mathopen {} \left ( P_1,  { \mathopen {} \left ( u_1;w_0:P_1 \vdash  P_0 \right ) \mathclose {}} \right ) \mathclose {}}</fr:tex>. Taking inverses and precomposing with <fr:tex>w_0</fr:tex> on both sides, we have <fr:tex>{ \mathopen {} \left ( P_0,w_0 \right ) \mathclose {}}  =  { \mathopen {} \left ( P_1,w_1 \right ) \mathclose {}}</fr:tex> using the fact that <fr:tex>w_0</fr:tex> is thunkable and inverse to <fr:tex>u_0</fr:tex>.</fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
